content.HowDoesThisWork_DisclaimerTextNonFE:
  &lt;div id=&quot;faq-expand-collapse&quot;&gt;
            &lt;span class=&quot;faq-heading-title&quot;&gt;What is the purpose of myOrangeMoney&#174;?&lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;div class=&quot;ui-faq-accordion-content-visible&quot;&gt;
                &lt;span&gt;
                    myOrangeMoney is an educational interactive online experience that was created to help you get a
                    clear picture of your monthly income needs in retirement and your current progress toward meeting
                    them and is not to be viewed as investment advice. Its interactive technology enables you to see
                    potential savings scenarios that are tailored to your personal circumstances, and supplies you with
                    the information you need that may help you to improve your retirement outlook. Whether your
                    retirement is five years away or 40, myOrangeMoney can help you understand how close you are to
                    being retirement ready.
                &lt;/span&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;br /&gt;
            &lt;div id=&quot;faq-accordion-expand-holder&quot;&gt;
                &lt;button id=&quot;faq-accordion-expand-all&quot;&gt;+ Expand All Items&lt;/button&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
            &lt;br /&gt;
            &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Privacy&quot;&gt;
                &lt;ol id=&quot;faq-sections-inner&quot; class=&quot;no-ol-numbering&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;Will any of the data I enter into myOrangeMoney be shared with my employer?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The numerical data you enter into myOrangeMoney, including any outside account
                                information, will not be shared with your employer in its original form. Voya will use
                                the data you enter, such as the age at which you’ll retire and your other retirement
                                savings and income, both to estimate your monthly retirement income and to calculate
                                your personalized &quot;replacement income&quot; (RI) score. See below for an explanation of the
                                RI score. Your calculated RI score will be shared with your employer to help your
                                employer assist its employees with retirement readiness.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What is an RI score?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Your RI score is a number between 1 and 100 that is derived from a series of
                                calculations based on your age, salary, deferral rate, retirement plan account balance,
                                any outside assets you enter into myOrangeMoney, and other publicly available
                                information. The underlying assumptions are proprietary to Voya and will not be shared
                                with your employer.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How will Voya use and secure the data I enter?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Voya is committed to protecting the privacy and confidentiality of your personal
                                information. Information entered into myOrangeMoney will be subject to the Voya
                                Financial Privacy Notice. Review the
                                &lt;a href=&quot;http://voya.com/privacy-notice&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Privacy Notice&lt;/a&gt; of the Voya
                                companies offering insurance, securities and related financial products and services in
                                the United States.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;If I call for assistance, to whom will I be connected?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                You will be directed to Voya’s Retirement Services Contact Center. Customer Service
                                Associates are available to help you complete transactions and to help you understand
                                how your plan works. Please note, Customer Service Associates are unable to provide
                                investment advice, however, they do have in-depth knowledge on how to use myOrangeMoney
                                and can also provide information to help you save more for retirement and make the most
                                of your participation in the plan.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Will the data I entered into myOrangeMoney be saved?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                There are a few places within the myOrangeMoney experience where you can save your data
                                so it is available upon your return visit. These include updates made to your &quot;Pension
                                /Other Retirement Savings &amp; Income&quot; field and some fields in &quot;About Me&quot;. Note, this may
                                exclude date of birth, annual pay, and pay frequency. If this information is provided by
                                your employer then this data will revert to the data on our recordkeeping system at the
                                beginning of each new session.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                In order to save the changes you made to the sliders (contributions, retirement age,
                                rate of return and social security checkbox election), select the &quot;Make Change Now&quot;
                                button. By clicking this button, it won&#39;t process a contribution change. If your plan
                                allows for online contribution rate changes, then select the &quot;I like it, let&#39;s do it&quot;
                                button and then accept the elections on the pre-confirmation screen.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ol&gt;
            &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
            &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How are myOrangeMoney estimates calculated?&quot;&gt;
                &lt;ol id=&quot;faq-sections-inner&quot; class=&quot;no-ol-numbering&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How is my retirement income goal determined?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Your retirement income goal is set to default to 70% (or a value set by your employer)
                                of your projected final year&#39;s pre-tax pay. You can also adjust this value as
                                appropriate to you in About Me. The salary used in this formula may be input by you or
                                provided by your employer and you have the ability to edit that figure as needed. This
                                is why we ask you to enter or confirm your annual pay or salary the first time you use
                                myOrangeMoney. If you have previously used My Retirement Overview (MRO) on the site, the
                                &quot;replacement income&quot; goal, and the salary you entered into MRO will automatically appear
                                in myOrangeMoney the first time you use it. Please check back at least once a year to
                                keep your information, including salary, current by clicking on About Me. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                The retirement income goal is an estimate of the income you may need in retirement to
                                maintain your standard of living. It represents an accepted standard in the financial
                                services industry, but it should only be viewed as a starting point for your retirement
                                planning. Your needs may require a different income goal, so you have the opportunity to
                                revise this percentage using the &quot;About Me&quot; button under the display. Please check back
                                at least once a year to keep your information, including salary, current by clicking on
                                About Me.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;Why isn&#39;t my retirement income set at 100% of my pre-tax pay?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Because your expenses may change when you stop working, 100% of your pre-retirement
                                income may not be required to maintain your standard of living in retirement. For
                                instance, some expenses may go down or go away, such as taxes and work-related expenses,
                                while some may go up, like health care costs and money you spend on new hobbies or
                                activities. Some examples of expenses that typically go down are:
                                &lt;ul class=&quot;bulletList&quot;&gt;
                                    &lt;li class=&quot;first&quot;&gt;
                                        Social Security and Medicare tax (FICA). This currently accounts for 7.65% of
                                        annual pay for most people.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        Annual Savings for Retirement are no longer needed. Depending on your savings
                                        rate and pay, this could equate to 14% of annual pay.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        As most people are generally in lower tax brackets after they retire, the amount
                                        you pay in taxes may go down.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        Living expenses and spending habits typically drop over the course of a 30 year
                                        retirement* equating to a 5-15% reduction in annual spending. *
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                &lt;/ul&gt;
                                *Research shows that individuals&#39; consumption gradually drops over the course of a 30
                                year retirement, even though health care costs typically increase as a percent of
                                overall consumption.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Are retiree health care costs included in my goal?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The default &quot;replacement income&quot; assumes coverage of retiree expenses including health
                                care costs. This is also true of any alternate percentage set by your employer. If you
                                feel your health care costs in retirement will be higher or lower than the default
                                estimate, you can modify your replacement income goal to be more or less than the
                                standard default value.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Can you explain how the health care modeling works?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                (If applicable) You can use the Retirement Healthcare feature to better estimate your
                                health care expenses in retirement. By confirming the state in which you plan to live in
                                retirement, we can illustrate the potential expenses you would incur at varying five
                                year increments, starting at age 65. The healthcare costs you might face in retirement
                                could also be higher or lower based on your particular needs or health condition. The
                                increase in costs is based on an inflation rate of 6.5% annually and is represented in
                                current dollars. The feature can help you to assess whether your income estimate is
                                adequate to meet your needs as you age. If not, you can consider additional savings
                                options. If applicable, your employer might also offer services or programs that can
                                help cover or reduce the cost of healthcare in retirement.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What is Medicare?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Medicare is our country’s health insurance program for people age 65 or older (Medicare
                                may also cover people under age 65 with certain disabilities and people of any age with
                                End-Stage Renal Disease). Unless you choose a Medicare Advantage Plan from a private
                                insurer (like an HMO or PPO), you may be entitled to benefits managed by the Federal
                                government including Medicare Part A benefits. You may also elect to purchase Medicare
                                Part B benefits, Part D or prescription drug coverage or Medicare Supplemental Coverage,
                                also referred to as Medigap Coverage.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                You may experience some additional healthcare related costs not covered by any of these
                                Medicare benefits. Costs associated with Long Term Care needs are not addressed by this
                                experience or estimate. Costs are in current dollars. If you retire before you are
                                eligible for Medicare you may choose to purchase private health insurance or to
                                self-insure. Costs and coverage for private health insurance varies greatly and are not
                                estimated in this experience.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Different parts of Medicare cover different services. The main parts of Medicare are
                                further summarized below.
                                &lt;ul class=&quot;bulletList&quot;&gt;
                                    &lt;li class=&quot;first&quot;&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Medicare Part A Hospital Insurance&lt;/b&gt; - Most people do not pay a premium in
                                        retirement for Part A if they or a spouse already paid for it through their
                                        payroll taxes while working. Medicare Part A helps cover inpatient care in
                                        hospitals, including critical access hospitals, and skilled nursing facilities
                                        (not custodial or long-term care). It also helps cover hospice care and some
                                        home health care. Beneficiaries must meet certain conditions to get these
                                        benefits. Note also that co-payments, coinsurance or deductibles may apply.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Medicare Part B Medical or Doctor’s Insurance&lt;/b&gt; - Most people pay a monthly
                                        premium in retirement for Part B. Medicare Part B helps cover medically
                                        necessary doctors&#39; services and outpatient care. It also covers some other
                                        medical services that Part A doesn&#39;t cover, such as some of the services of
                                        physical and occupational therapists, and some home health care. Part B premiums
                                        are uniform nationally and are increased for those with a higher Modified
                                        Adjusted Gross Income.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Medicare Part C Supplemental premium or Medigap&lt;/b&gt; - Medigap or Medicare
                                        Part C coverage is optional and is provided through insurance policies issues by
                                        private insurers (Plans A-N). You may incur out-of-pocket healthcare expenses,
                                        for costs not covered by Medicare benefits and Medigap insurance.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Medicare Part D Prescription Drug coverage&lt;/b&gt; - Part D coverage is optional.
                                        Premiums are increased for those with a higher Modified Adjusted Gross Income,
                                        differ from state to state, and vary based on the specific plan and level of
                                        benefit selected. Most people will pay a monthly premium for this coverage.
                                        Everyone with Medicare can get this coverage that may help lower prescription
                                        drug costs and help protect against higher costs in the future. Medicare
                                        Prescription Drug Coverage is insurance. Private companies provide the coverage.
                                        Beneficiaries choose the drug plan and pay a monthly premium. Like other
                                        insurance, if a beneficiary decides not to enroll in a drug plan when they are
                                        first eligible, they may pay a penalty if they choose to join later.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Out-of-Pocket&lt;/b&gt; - This is estimated and refers to healthcare costs not
                                        covered by any of the above plans. Examples of possible costs include dental,
                                        vision, hearing aids, medications not covered by Part D, copays, deductibles or
                                        other services not covered by Medigap.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Pre-Medicare Supplemental&lt;/b&gt; - If you retire before age 65, you may need to
                                        purchase private health insurance (or self-insure). Costs and coverage vary
                                        greatly. Pricing for Affordable Care Act eligible plans may be researched at
                                        &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.healthcare.gov&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; www.healthcare.gov&lt;/a&gt;.
                                        This experience does not provide estimates for private insurance should you
                                        choose to retire before age 65.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                &lt;/ul&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Please consult Medicare.gov for a complete description of Medicare. The summary above
                                was prepared from the publication Medicare and You found at
                                &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.medicare.gov/pubs/pdf/10050-Medicare-and-You.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;
                                    https://www.medicare.gov/pubs/pdf/10050-Medicare-and-You.pdf&lt;/a
                                &gt;
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What is Medicaid?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If you cannot afford to pay your Medicare premiums and other medical costs, you may be
                                able to get help. Medicaid is a joint federal and state government program that helps
                                low-income retirees cover healthcare expenses. Each state has its own rules about who is
                                eligible and what is covered under Medicaid. Some people qualify for both Medicare and
                                Medicaid. Medicaid covers most basic health services and many costs not covered by
                                Medicare like prescription drugs, nursing home care, eye exams, glasses, and more.
                                Medicaid may also help to pay for Medicare costs. For more information about the
                                Medicaid program, contact your local medical assistance agency, social services or
                                welfare office. This feature does not consider whether you will be eligible for Medicaid
                                and estimates Medicare and other retiree health care costs the same way for everyone.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What if I already have medical insurance?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If you already have other health insurance when you become eligible for Medicare, you
                                should consider whether it is worth the monthly premium cost to sign up for Medicare
                                medical insurance. The answer varies with each person and the kind of other health
                                insurance you may have. You should speak with the appropriate resource for your
                                circumstances. If applicable, your employer might also offer services or programs that
                                can help cover or reduce the cost of healthcare in retirement. If you are still working
                                and covered by your employer group health plan, speak to your personnel or benefits
                                office. If you are not covered under an employer plan, reach out to your advisor or
                                insurance agent for assistance. If you expect to have additional income at retirement to
                                cover healthcare related expenses such as a health savings account or a retiree medical
                                account, you can enter it in Other Retirement Savings and Income and it will be included
                                in your income estimate.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;Where do you get my pay to determine my retirement income goal?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                myOrangeMoney uses the compensation amount provided by you or your employer. You can
                                always revise the amount of your pay using the &quot;About Me&quot; button under the display. Be
                                aware that if you revise a salary figure set by your employer, it will only be valid for
                                the current session, and will revert to the employer-provided salary the next time you
                                login to your account. If you have previously used My Retirement Overview (MRO) on the
                                site, any salary you entered into MRO will automatically appear in myOrangeMoney upon
                                your first use.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Current Pay and contribution amounts used to calculate your income estimate, in
                                myOrangeMoney, are limited based on laws that govern retirement plans, such as how much
                                money can be contributed annually on a before-tax basis. The maximum annual pay that may
                                be considered in the experience is constrained by compensation limits that are set
                                annually by the IRS, [(IRC Section 401(a)(17)]. Amounts in excess of the IRC limits are
                                not considered in myOrangeMoney when determining how much you can defer as a percent of
                                salary each year. For example, if the current IRC limit is $270,000 and your pay is
                                $300,000, only the first $270,000 of your pay would be considered as a basis for
                                contributions. So, in this scenario, if your stated contribution were 6 % of annual pay,
                                the deferral amount would be $16,200 per year, not $18,000.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;b&gt; Please note:&lt;/b&gt; the pay or salary you enter for modeling, will be used when
                                calculating your retirement income goal. For example, if you show an annual pay of
                                $300,000 and an income replacement percentage of 70%, your retirement income goal will
                                be set to 70% of that figure, or $210,000 per year. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                myOrangeMoney assumes a 3% annual pay increase but you are always able to change that
                                value in “About Me” under Personal Information. The percentage increase you enter will
                                impact retirement income estimates made by myOrangeMoney, including your estimated
                                Social Security income and future payroll contributions, if shown as a percentage of
                                your pay.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Can I use myOrangeMoney if I leave my current job?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Yes. You would be able to enter a salary from any source in order to determine your
                                retirement income goal. Contributions from your pay being made outside of this plan
                                would default to 0% and you will be able to estimate the impact of additional savings.
                                In addition, savings made to plans other than your current employer&#39;s plan can be
                                entered using the &quot;Other Retirement Savings and Income&quot; feature of the experience.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;Can I use myOrangeMoney if I am retired, or do not have a current income?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                No. This experience is designed to calculate your retirement income goal based on a
                                percent of current income. Without a current income, it will be unable to calculate a
                                goal.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ol&gt;
            &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
            &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;General Questions&quot;&gt;
                &lt;ol id=&quot;faq-sections-inner&quot; class=&quot;no-ol-numbering&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&#39;Why do you want to know how I &quot;feel&quot; about retirement?&#39;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                How you feel about retirement is important because it generally reflects how comfortable
                                you are with your retirement planning. Our goal is to make sure you know where you stand
                                regarding your readiness to retire at every point in your career, and to provide you
                                with the tools that may improve your retirement outlook. We believe having this
                                knowledge and these features at your disposal can help you feel more in control of your
                                retirement planning and more confident about your financial future.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Is this the same income estimate provided on my statement?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                No. The income estimate provided on your statement is based on the assumptions that: you
                                will not make any further additions to your retirement plan, have no additional
                                retirement assets and are currently planning to retire today at age 65. Your statement
may also include income benefits such as an outside annuity or pension (if applicable).

                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;What is the Organize My $$$ feature and how can it help me prepare for retirement?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                This feature is not available to every client. No matter how close or far away your
                                retirement is, how much you can save for it will be dependent to some extent on your
                                current financial situation. &quot;Organize My $$$&quot; lays out multiple aspects of your
                                financial picture, including household data, in a digital &quot;Personal Financial
                                Dashboard&quot;, which enables you to monitor a consolidated picture of your overall
                                financial health in one multi-view status report. The &quot;Organize My $$$&quot; dashboard is a
                                component of a holistic planning process that can help you explore your savings options
                                and design and manage your plan, as well as providing access to recommendations that are
                                tailored to fit your particular needs and goals. Please note, information entered into
                                the dashboard will not automatically get included in myOrangeMoney.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;What is the Special Needs planning for you or a loved one feature?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The need for retirement planning expands when you or a loved one has a disability.
                                Understanding what it could mean and preparing early can equal success for you and those
                                dear to you. This feature allows you to model additional benefits at retirement, if
                                applicable. It also allows you to re-evaluate your monthly savings goal at retirement.
                                If you have a disability or may be caring for a loved one with a disability during your
                                retirement, you may need to save more to cover additional expenses.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;

                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;What if I have two plans with the same employer on your system?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Balances and payroll contributions for both plans will be included in your myOrangeMoney
                                estimate.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;What if I have two Voya plans from different employers on your system?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If you log into your plan using the same Website address for both Voya plans, both plan
                                balances will be included in your myOrangeMoney estimate. Contributions to the qualified
                                plans where you have an active status will be included in your myOrangeMoney estimate.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How do the contribution sliders work?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If Voya manages contribution changes for your plan the contribution slider for each
                                money source will reflect the current contribution amount or paycheck deduction that is
                                on file with us. The maximum value for each slider is determined by your Plan&#39;s
                                contribution limit per paycheck, and values on the sliders will be in dollars and/or
                                percent depending on your Plan&#39;s rules.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                If Voya does not manage contributions from your pay for your plan, each contribution
                                slider initially defaults to 0, unless you have used My Retirement Overview (MRO)
                                previous to your first use of myOrangeMoney. If you did use MRO, the values you see on
                                your first visit will be prefilled with the MRO values. The maximum value on each slider
                                will be the current IRS maximum amount allowed per paycheck for the money source you
                                choose to model. Values you insert as your contribution amounts or rates are the ones
                                that will be reflected on the sliders the next time you visit myOrangeMoney.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                If you are no longer working for this employer, the sliders will allow you to model
                                contributions from your pay that you may be able to make outside of this plan. These are
                                general and reflect the maximum value allowed per paycheck based on the current year&#39;s
                                IRS limit for the money source you choose to model.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/voya-expand-collapse
            &gt;

            &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Estimated Retirement Income&quot;&gt;
                &lt;ol id=&quot;faq-sections-inner&quot; class=&quot;no-ol-numbering&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Why do you need my date of birth?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Your date of birth is needed to calculate your future retirement income estimate, which
                                is based on the estimated growth of your assets between now and the time you intend to
                                retire. If we already show your birth date in myOrangeMoney, it is because we have it
                                from your employer. You should note that while you can modify when you were born for
                                modeling purposes, any changes you make to your date of birth will not be saved in our
                                files. If the date we show is incorrect, you must contact your employer to change it
                                officially. If you are no longer employed, you can contact Customer Service for
                                assistance with updating this information.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What are the components of my future estimated income?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Your &lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;estimated monthly retirement income&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt; is calculated as a percentage of
                                your current pre-tax pay and may include multiple components, with values that we have
                                estimated on your behalf or that you have provided to us directly. These sources
                                include: your future retirement account balance (including ongoing contributions by you
                                and/or your employer), pension benefits, Social Security retirement benefits, and other
                                retirement income you identify. A shortfall is presented if your monthly retirement
                                income goal is estimated to exceed your estimated monthly retirement income. A surplus
                                is presented if your monthly retirement income goal is estimated to be less than your
                                estimated monthly retirement income. The estimates utilize generally accepted financial
                                calculations, as well as requirements set forth by the Financial Industry Regulatory
                                Authority (FINRA). &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Each time you visit myOrangeMoney, you&#39;ll see your progress toward meeting your monthly
                                retirement income goal graphically represented as a &quot;dollar bill&quot; display that
                                illustrates an estimate of where you stand given your personal parameters. These
                                estimates are hypothetical, for illustrative purposes only and do not represent current
                                or future performance of any specific investment. Investments carry a degree of risk and
                                past performance is not a guarantee of future results. Generally speaking, the greater
                                the return, the greater the risk.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Please check back at least once a year to keep your information, including salary,
                                current by clicking on About Me.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How are my paycheck contributions incorporated?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                &lt;b&gt;Contributions per paycheck&lt;/b&gt; (if applicable) are assumed to be made at the
                                beginning of each pay period, to increase annually at a rate equal to that of any stated
                                salary increase and are assumed to grow by the stated investment rate of return until
                                you reach your designated retirement age. Contribution amounts are constrained each year
                                so as not to exceed the maximum limit set by your Plan or the IRS, whichever limit is
                                lower. If you participate in an automatic savings program, future increases to your
                                contributions are not considered. It is also assumed that no additional contributions
                                will be made after the designated retirement age is reached. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;b&gt;Employer contributions&lt;/b&gt; (if applicable) are assumed to be made according to the
                                formula provided by your employer and displayed in “About Me” and assumed to grow by the
                                stated investment rate of return, until you reach your designated retirement age.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;Does it matter if I start contributing part-way through the year?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Partial first year contributions are treated as full year contributions. Due to the
                                compounding effect of investments, your income estimate may be overstated. For example,
                                if you begin contributing in June, myOrangeMoney will estimate your future income
                                assuming you began contributing in January of that first contribution year.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Can I model catchup contribution if I’m under 50?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Catchup contributions can only be modeled if you are currently eligible to make them. If
                                you are currently under 50 and plan to make catchup contributions in the future, your
                                income estimate may be understated.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;How does myOrangeMoney handle after-tax contributions (e.g., if I&#39;m contributing to a Roth 401k)?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Your estimated monthly retirement income is displayed in today&#39;s dollars and does not
                                account for any federal or state income tax. You may have already paid taxes on that
                                future income by making Roth contributions. The retirement income illustration will
                                consider your projected future Roth contributions and current balance, and the estimate
                                will gross up that value by 25% to convert to a pre-tax dollar value to express your
                                retirement income forecast in pre-tax dollars.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                When your tax obligations are considered, your net retirement income may be
                                significantly different. You should consult a qualified professional legal, financial
                                and/or tax advisor when making decisions related to your individual tax situation.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;What if I am planning on other sources of income in retirement?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                You can include other planned sources of income in retirement by using the &quot;Other
                                Retirement Savings &amp; Income&quot; feature located in the &quot;Let&#39;s talk about&quot; menu. Some
                                examples may be future pension benefits, current IRA balances, Non-qualified accounts,
                                healthcare savings accounts or additional annual savings you are making towards a
                                retirement account. The assets or income you identify will be represented in the
                                estimate of progress towards your estimated monthly retirement income goal. Please note,
                                your employer may have setup an automatic ‘feed’ of outside account information. If so,
                                they will have pre-determined whether those assets are factored into your retirement
                                account balance or not. If they are not included, they can be added manually in the
                                “Other Retirement Savings &amp; Income&quot; feature.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Your
                                &lt;b
                                    &gt;current account balance in your retirement plan(s) and current balances in other
                                    retirement assets you identify&lt;/b
                                &gt;
                                (e.g., an IRA) are assumed to grow by the stated investment rate of return selected on
                                the slider, until your designated retirement age is reached.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How is Social Security incorporated into the illustration?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                &lt;b&gt;Social Security benefit estimates&lt;/b&gt; (if applicable) are based on the Social
                                Security Administration&#39;s Primary Insurance Amount table, which defines Social Security
                                retirement benefits at normal retirement age. If you do not think you will be eligible
                                or do not wish to include Social Security in your income estimate, you can remove it
                                from your illustration by locating Social Security in the &quot;Let&#39;s talk about&quot; menu and
                                clicking off the checkmark via the “Include Social Security” election or check box. If
                                you state that you have no current pay or salary, we cannot estimate your Social
                                Security retirement benefit. If you believe you are eligible to receive benefits, you
                                can manually enter your own monthly benefit estimate at your normal retirement age.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                In order to provide an estimate (if applicable), your earnings history is approximated
                                using your current age, retirement age, annual pay or salary, and annual pay increases.
                                Under most circumstances, Social Security retirement benefits cannot be collected prior
                                to age 62. So, for illustrative purposes, benefit estimates you see in myOrangeMoney
                                will be those that would be available starting at age 62 even if your designated
                                retirement age is younger than age 62. If you were born before 1938, your full
                                retirement age is 65. The full retirement age increases gradually to 67 for people born
                                in 1960 or later.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;i&gt;Collect Benefits Early&lt;/i&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Some people retire before their full retirement age. You can retire as early as 62 and
                                take benefits at a reduced rate. If you elect to claim benefits early, the result for
                                you (and your spouse, if applicable) could potentially be tens of thousands of dollars
                                in reduced lifetime benefits.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;i&gt;Collect Benefits Later&lt;/i&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                If you continue to work after your full retirement age, you can receive higher benefits
                                because of additional earnings and credits for delayed retirement. According to the
                                Social Security Administration, the benefit available to you could rise by 6-8% each
                                year that you delay taking your benefit, up to age 70. The amount of the increase
                                depends on the year you were born. If you can wait three years before you collect, you
                                could potentially experience a permanent 24% increase in benefit payments.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                After you turn 70, the amount of your payments is locked in. For illustration purposes,
                                Social Security payment estimates are not modeled beyond age 70.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                If you do not qualify for Social Security benefits on your own, you may be eligible for
                                spousal benefits. You could receive up to 50% of your spouse’s full benefit, even if you
                                have earnings and work history.
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                Due to the complexity of calculating future benefits, these are just rough estimates.
                                More precise benefit estimates are available from the Social Security Administration.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;What if I may be subject to the Windfall Elimination Provision (WEP)?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The Windfall Elimination Provision (WEP) affects how the amount of your retirement
                                benefit is calculated if you receive a pension from work where Social Security taxes
                                were not taken out of your pay. According to the Social Security Administration, if you
                                work for an employer who does not withhold Social Security taxes from your salary, any
                                pension you get based on that work may reduce your Social Security benefits. A modified
                                formula is used to calculate your benefit amount, resulting in a lower Social Security
                                benefit than you otherwise would receive. If you are subject to the WEP, you can use the
                                &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ssa.gov/retire2/anyPiaWepjs04.htm&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;
                                    WEP calculator on the Social Security website
                                &lt;/a&gt;
                                to estimate your benefit payments. Enter the monthly retirement benefit estimate from
                                the WEP calculator into myOrangeMoney.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What if I have a pension?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If you provide a &lt;b&gt;monthly pension benefit estimate&lt;/b&gt; for a specific retirement age,
                                and subsequently provide a new retirement age, you need to provide the pension benefit
                                corresponding to that new retirement age. Also note that monthly pension benefit
                                estimates must be entered in today&#39;s dollars. If you receive a monthly pension income
                                estimate from your employer expressed in future dollars, use our
                                &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.voyaretirementplans.com/ark-pwe/CalcPV.htm&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;
                                    &gt;conversion calculator to convert them into today&#39;s dollars&lt;/a
                                &gt;. Then return to the &quot;Other Retirement Savings &amp; Income&quot; feature located in the &quot;Let&#39;s
                                talk about&quot; menu of myOrangeMoney and update your monthly pension income amount in
                                today&#39;s dollars. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                (As applicable) You may also be able to model pension benefits if you work for a public
                                pension or government plan administered by Voya. In this case, you can use the ‘Other
                                Retirement Savings &amp; Income’ section and select the ‘chose a retirement system’ option.
                                From there, you will be able to select the applicable state, pension system and years of
                                service to better estimate your benefit. Once you save your selections, you will see the
                                pension estimate in the pension slice of the dollar bill, With this feature, you can
                                adjust your retirement age from the slider and see the impact to your pension benefit
                                immediately. Note that these estimates are expressed in today’s dollars.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How do you know what my investments may return each year?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The rate of return (the money your investments make) used in myOrangeMoney is set to 6%,
                                which is the standard industry default for a moderately conservative investor. If a 3%
                                inflation rate is assumed, this equates to a 3% real rate of return. You may adjust this
                                rate based on your style of investing or if you feel the rate of return for your own
                                investments will be higher or lower than 6%.&lt;i&gt;
                                    Here&#39;s our tip: When designating a rate of return for modeling, consider an average
                                    annual return realized over a period of at least five years if possible, since
                                    retirement investing is generally done over many years. Often there is a display of
                                    your current actual year-to-date rate of return on the retirement plan home page,
                                    located directly below myOrangeMoney. You can also see a longer period rate of
                                    return using the personal rate of return function from the Account menu. You may
                                    adjust the &quot;what my investments may return each year&quot; slider based on your personal
                                    selected investments.&lt;/i
                                &gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
                                It&#39;s important to keep in mind that if you do change the &quot;what my investments may return
                                each year&quot; slider, there is no automatic investment election change or investment fund
                                transfer made on your behalf. If you would like to change the way your future
                                contributions are invested or rebalance your current asset allocation, you must initiate
                                these transactions yourself, selecting the appropriate menu option under the Accounts
                                menu. Also remember that, generally speaking, the greater the return, the greater the
                                risk associated with achieving that return.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How is my estimate impacted by investment rate of return?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                For the purposes of the model, the investment rate of return you select and input is
                                assumed to be constant during the period in which your assets accumulate. Any selection
                                you make on the &quot;what my investments may return each year&quot; slider will be reflected in
                                your estimate. For example, if you choose a rate of return above the default 6%, your
                                income estimate will be higher, if you select a return below 6%, your income estimate
                                will be lower. However, it&#39;s very important to keep in mind that investment rates of
                                return you model do not in any way impact the investment selections in your retirement
                                plan, which generally speaking may be affected by market volatility. Monte Carlo
                                probability analysis, which considers the volatility of investment returns over time, is
                                not used in the myOrangeMoney analysis.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How is my estimated monthly income calculated?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                &lt;b&gt;Retirement income estimates&lt;/b&gt; for your current account balance, future
                                contributions from your pay, an income solution (if applicable), and any applicable
                                employer contributions or other assets set aside for retirement are for illustrative
                                purposes only and are not guaranteed. Income estimates are based on the assumption you
                                will make a lump sum purchase of a single life immediate annuity at retirement that pays
                                you a level income amount each month for as long as you live. Using this annuity
                                assumption allows us to translate your estimated retirement portfolio into terms that
                                are similar to other monthly retirement income sources such as Social Security or any
                                pension benefits you may have. The estimated income amount shown is the income you would
                                receive at retirement in terms of today&#39;s dollars, but you should be aware that
                                inflation will erode your spending power over time. For most plans, the estimated amount
                                of the annuity income payment is based on the combination of the Society of Actuaries&#39;
                                Annuity 2000 Basic Mortality Table and a recent 10-year constant maturity U.S. Treasury securities yield rate. This rate fluctuates based on market conditions and is updated at the beginning of each month.
                                Some employers may have provided plan specific annuity rates. If applicable the plan
                                specific information would be located in the Message Center. If you have a guaranteed
                                income solution, that amount will be represented as an estimated future or actual
                                withdrawal amount in View Details. Please keep in mind that this approach to generating
                                your income estimate does not constitute a recommendation to purchase an annuity at
                                retirement. Each individual&#39;s retirement needs are different, and an annuity purchase
                                may or may not make sense for you.
                                &lt;ul class=&quot;bulletList&quot;&gt;
                                    &lt;li class=&quot;first&quot;&gt;
                                        The estimates illustrate retirement needs &lt;b&gt;for a single person&lt;/b&gt; and do not
                                        take into account spousal or beneficiary information (unless added in Other
                                        Retirement Savings).
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        The values displayed have been
                                        &lt;b&gt;rounded to the nearest dollar for display purposes&lt;/b&gt;. Therefore, you may
                                        notice a small discrepancy between the individual components that make up the
                                        dollar bill slices and the value of the whole bill. The percent of goal value is
                                        also a rounded value for display purposes.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        Stated retirement age is capped at age 80. If you plan to work after this age,
                                        enter income as &quot;outside assets&quot; to be reflected in your future income estimate.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;A &lt;b&gt;2.3% annual inflation rate&lt;/b&gt; is assumed.&lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Neither Federal nor State income taxes&lt;/b&gt; have been factored into the
                                        illustration.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                &lt;/ul&gt;
                                Visual of the process:
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;img
                                    src=&quot;/static/global/images/eom/process_visual2_enus.png&quot;
                                    title=&quot;Visual of the process&quot;
                                /&gt;
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;How does this estimate compare with other retirement income estimates on your site?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                There are several tools currently available on the site that also provide retirement
                                income estimates.
                                &lt;ul class=&quot;bulletList&quot;&gt;
                                    &lt;li class=&quot;first&quot;&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;My Retirement Overview&lt;/b&gt; - This tool uses the same accumulation
                                        calculations as myOrangeMoney but it provides an annual cash flow analysis
                                        during retirement rather than a monthly income estimate. It also differs from
                                        myOrangeMoney in that it defaults to a replacement income in retirement of 100%
                                        of your current salary, inflated to your retirement age. In addition, MRO offers
                                        a retirement benefit estimate for public retirement systems and includes an
                                        integrated paycheck analysis tool.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;&quot;Organize My $$$&quot; 10 Minute Path&lt;/b&gt; (if available to you) - This tool uses a
                                        similar estimation method as myOrangeMoney but displays the results in terms of
                                        &quot;years of retirement funded.&quot; It defaults to a replacement income of 80% of your
                                        current salary inflated to your retirement age.
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                    &lt;li&gt;
                                        &lt;b&gt;Income estimate shown on statement&lt;/b&gt; - The income estimate shown on your
                                        monthly or quarterly statement is based on the assumption that you will not make
                                        any further additions to your retirement plan, have no additional retirement
                                        assets, other than those reflected on the statement, and are planning to retire
                                        today, at age 65. This estimate reflects the income that would be generated if
                                        you were currently age 65 and the current balance in your account(s) were used
                                        to purchase a single premium immediate annuity. Your statement may also include
                                        income benefits such as an outside annuity or pension (if applicable).
                                    &lt;/li&gt;
                                &lt;/ul&gt;
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ol&gt;&lt;/voya-expand-collapse
            &gt;
            &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Contribution Changes and Data Input&quot;&gt;
                &lt;ol id=&quot;faq-sections-inner&quot; class=&quot;no-ol-numbering&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;How do I update the amount of pay I can save now from this display?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Use the &quot;Make Change Now&quot; button on the bottom of the right slide of the display. If
                                your plan allows for online contribution rate changes, this button will guide you
                                through verification and a direct update process, and your changes will be effective
                                within one to two payroll cycles. If your plan does not enable you to make contribution
                                rate changes through the site, you will be able to make them through the standard
                                contribution rate change process established by your employer.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What does the Reset button do?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The Reset button simply allows you to reset the sliders back to where they were when you
                                entered the session. This is a convenience feature that enables you to model various
                                scenarios without requesting any actual changes to your account.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;How do I include my spouse or partner&#39;s income in the estimates?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                While myOrangeMoney does not currently have specific spouse/partner planning features,
                                you can include your spouse/partner&#39;s income in your goal by increasing your goal above
                                the 70% (or the value set by your employer) replacement income default. You should make
                                sure that you also include your spouse/partner&#39;s contribution to your progress by
                                entering balances, ongoing contributions, and future expected retirement income using
                                the &quot;Other Retirement Savings &amp;amp; Income&quot; feature located in the &quot;Let&#39;s talk about&quot;
                                menu. This could include your spouse/partner&#39;s expected social security amount as well.
                                Note, however, that myOrangeMoney is set up to reflect only one retirement age (yours).
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What if I currently have multiple sources of income?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                You can enter additional current income as &quot;Other Retirement Savings &amp;amp; Income.&quot; You
                                can also increase your monthly retirement income goal to accommodate the additional
                                income.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What if I am no longer working with this employer?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                You can adjust the &quot;Amount of my pay I can save now&quot; slider to model savings amounts
                                that you might be able to make with another employer. This can help you continue to
                                model your estimated income needs and potential gap. Save your changes using the &quot;Make
                                Change Now&quot; button.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ol&gt;
            &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;

            &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;Loan Options in myOrangeMoney&quot;&gt;
                &lt;ol id=&quot;faq-sections-inner&quot; class=&quot;no-ol-numbering&quot;&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;When would this feature be available to me?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If your plan has the myOrangeMoney loan feature enabled, you will be able to select
                                “Let’s talk about your loan options” when you can request a loan or if you have an
                                active loan.
                                &lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;Please Note&lt;/b&gt;: Your plan may require that you meet other conditions in order
                                to take a loan. The myOrangeMoney loan feature does not consider existing loans you may
                                have with other investment providers. Plan requirements and/or loan terms will determine
                                the availability of a loan and the available loan amount.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse
                            heading-text=&quot;&gt;When I model taking a new loan, how is the impact to my retirement income calculated?&quot;
                        &gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                The estimated income from the modeled loan amount and is subtracted from your current
                                estimated retirement income. By selecting the ? icon next to the &quot;After Loan amount&quot;
                                text, or by selecting the “See the value of repayment link”, you can also see the
                                estimated value of making your scheduled payments.
                                &lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;The assumption for retirement age and rate of return are setup in the retirement
                                savings view of myOrangeMoney. A 2.3% annual inflation rate is assumed.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;How are my outstanding loans treated?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                Your estimated retirement income does not assume future loan payments. To see an
                                estimate for the value of making your remaining scheduled loan payments, you can select
                                “Let’s talk about your loan options” and then select “View Details”. The estimated value
                                of future loan payments is labeled “From Future Loan Payments”.
                                &lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;If you have defaulted on a loan, no additional payments are assumed. Please note
                                that you may incur additional penalties and/or taxes when you default on a loan, those
                                scenarios are not illustrated.
                                &lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;The assumption for retirement age and rate of return are setup in the retirement
                                savings view of myOrangeMoney. A 2.30% annual inflation rate is assumed.
                                &lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;Please Note&lt;/b&gt;: The myOrangeMoney loan feature does not consider existing
                                loans you may have with other investment providers.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What if I retire before my loan is paid off?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                If your estimated retirement age occurs before your last scheduled loan payment, the
                                estimate assumes that the loan will be repaid in full at the time of retirement.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                    &lt;li&gt;
                        &lt;voya-expand-collapse heading-text=&quot;What happens if I don’t make my loan payments?&quot;&gt;
                            &lt;div&gt;
                                You&#39;ll have to pay taxes on the total outstanding loan balance. And you will also need
                                to pay a 10% premature distribution penalty, unless an exception applies, if you&#39;re
                                under age 59&#189;. Any unpaid amount will continue to accrue interest until there is a
                                distributable event and will count against your future loan availability.
                                &lt;br /&gt;
                                &lt;br /&gt;Keep in mind that if you leave your job, you generally have a limited time to pay
                                off the loan. If your plan allows the loan to continue, your payment method may need to
                                change.
                            &lt;/div&gt;
                        &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;
                    &lt;/li&gt;
                &lt;/ol&gt;
            &lt;/voya-expand-collapse&gt;

            &lt;br /&gt;
            &lt;br /&gt;
            &lt;i
                &gt;No representations, warranties or guarantees are made as to the accuracy of any illustrations or
                calculations. Neither Voya Retirement Insurance and Annuity Company nor Voya Institutional Plan
                Services, LLC shall be liable for any damages or costs of any type arising out of or in any way
                connected with your use of this calculator. This information does not serve, either directly or
                indirectly, as legal, financial or tax advice and you should always consult a qualified professional
                legal, financial and/or tax advisor when making decisions related to your individual tax situation.
                &lt;br /&gt;
                &lt;br /&gt;
            &lt;/i&gt;
            CN2010083_0224
        &lt;/div&gt;

content.HelpText_RORSliderHelp:
&lt;h4&gt;Select the investment style/rate of return that reflects your comfort level with risk.&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We have provided a range of returns because rates will vary over time particularly for long term investments. Past performance is not a guarantee of future results.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Conservative &lt;/strong&gt;(1-4%) investors tend to seek stability and are more concerned with protecting their current assets than increasing their value.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Moderate &lt;/strong&gt;(5-8%) investors are concerned with consistent growth, and are willing to tolerate more risk in their investments in exchange for potentially higher returns.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Aggressive &lt;/strong&gt;(9-12%) investors are willing to accept potentially higher levels of risk in exchange for higher levels of growth and are comfortable with volatility and fluctuations over the short to medium term as long as they can increase the value of assets over the long term.&lt;/p&gt;

